AUDIENCE: Do we as
creatures-- is--

00:50:58.788 --> 00:51:01.850
we tend to be rather curious,
and does that makes us somewhat

00:51:01.850 --> 00:51:03.244
different from other animals?

00:51:03.244 --> 00:51:04.910
JAMIE JONES: You know,
there are a lot--

00:51:04.910 --> 00:51:09.080
I think that anything that
makes its living as a generalist

00:51:09.080 --> 00:51:11.640
is going to be curious.

00:51:11.640 --> 00:51:13.490
Lots of primates are
super curious, right?

00:51:13.490 --> 00:51:18.260
I mean, if you live around
here and you have French doors,

00:51:18.260 --> 00:51:20.930
you've possibly seen
raccoons at your door,

00:51:20.930 --> 00:51:22.740
just sort of like
looking in, like, hey,

00:51:22.740 --> 00:51:24.530
what's going on in there?

00:51:24.530 --> 00:51:26.510
So I don't know if curiosity--

00:51:26.510 --> 00:51:28.970
we certainly take
curiosity to another level.

00:51:28.970 --> 00:51:31.490
All of those things--

00:51:31.490 --> 00:51:33.560
you know, if you go to
Mars and you come back,

00:51:33.560 --> 00:51:36.740
that's a pretty high
status thing to do, right?

00:51:36.740 --> 00:51:39.422
You have a social
signaling going on--

00:51:39.422 --> 00:51:40.130
if you come back.

00:51:40.130 --> 00:51:41.600
No, right.

00:51:41.600 --> 00:51:44.900
And if you think about
my Bayesian model,

00:51:44.900 --> 00:51:47.180
how many opportunities do
you have to learn about what

00:51:47.180 --> 00:51:49.890
the actual hazard is?

00:51:49.890 --> 00:51:52.540
Suppose you have like
a really flat prior.

00:51:52.540 --> 00:51:55.610
You've never seen anyone
go to Mars, so you know,

00:51:55.610 --> 00:51:58.670
it could be anything, right?

00:51:58.670 --> 00:52:00.680
So I think that that
sort of explains

00:52:00.680 --> 00:52:06.050
some of the unusual decisions
that people seem to make.

00:52:06.050 --> 00:52:10.670
Moving into the Arctic to live--

00:52:10.670 --> 00:52:14.030
it may seem uncomfortable to us,
but you know, if you're Inuit,

00:52:14.030 --> 00:52:16.790
you do pretty well, in general.

00:52:16.790 --> 00:52:21.450
And there's a living
to be made there,

00:52:21.450 --> 00:52:24.860
and people are
incredibly adaptable.

00:52:24.860 --> 00:52:27.100
AUDIENCE: Question--
thanks for the talk.

00:52:27.100 --> 00:52:31.500
Do you see any other species
that have environment--

00:52:31.500 --> 00:52:34.390
that evolved in uncertain
environments that share

00:52:34.390 --> 00:52:36.984
a similar pattern in
reproductive power or other

00:52:36.984 --> 00:52:37.900
characteristics that--

00:52:37.900 --> 00:52:40.887
JAMIE JONES: Yeah,
that's a great question.

00:52:40.887 --> 00:52:41.720
I don't really know.

00:52:41.720 --> 00:52:45.170
There is a-- so the
classic bet hedgers are--

00:52:45.170 --> 00:52:47.120
there are a bunch of birds.

00:52:47.120 --> 00:52:49.790
Again, local environment,
red-tailed hawks, right?

00:52:49.790 --> 00:52:52.610
So a lot of the raptors
will do this thing

00:52:52.610 --> 00:52:56.180
that's really kind of
perplexing at face value.

00:52:56.180 --> 00:52:58.700
They'll lay clutches
of two eggs,

00:52:58.700 --> 00:53:02.480
but only one will
ever fledge, and it

00:53:02.480 --> 00:53:04.820
seems incredibly wasteful.

00:53:04.820 --> 00:53:07.200
And it's a classic
bet hedging thing.

00:53:07.200 --> 00:53:09.740
If that first one fails,
then the second one

00:53:09.740 --> 00:53:13.280
is there, and the cost--

00:53:13.280 --> 00:53:15.110
you're paying a little
bit of your mean.

00:53:15.110 --> 00:53:19.460
You're paying out a
little insurance policy

00:53:19.460 --> 00:53:21.780
to insure against
catastrophic failure.

00:53:21.780 --> 00:53:23.720
So there are lots
of birds that engage

00:53:23.720 --> 00:53:26.570
in this type of bet hedging.

00:53:26.570 --> 00:53:29.030
Reproductive power,
as I've called it,

00:53:29.030 --> 00:53:31.310
I have not seen
it in any mammal.

00:53:31.310 --> 00:53:32.900
It's possible it
exists in other--

00:53:32.900 --> 00:53:36.210
but you know, the way
the Chernov model works,

00:53:36.210 --> 00:53:39.020
you have to-- for this model,
you have to be a mammal.

00:53:39.020 --> 00:53:42.980
You could come up with these
sort of dimensionless design

00:53:42.980 --> 00:53:45.380
features of different
life histories,

00:53:45.380 --> 00:53:47.360
but it only works
for if you have

00:53:47.360 --> 00:53:51.026
the same kind of general
reproductive biology.

00:53:51.026 --> 00:53:51.870
Yeah.

00:53:51.870 --> 00:53:54.699
AUDIENCE: So in light
of your research, maybe

00:53:54.699 --> 00:53:57.240
academically you wouldn't make
any recommendations like this,

00:53:57.240 --> 00:54:00.150
but personally, do you
have recommendations

00:54:00.150 --> 00:54:03.810
on how to motivate
people psychologically

00:54:03.810 --> 00:54:06.900
and collectively to address
issues like climate change

00:54:06.900 --> 00:54:10.470
that we're feeling
in the present now,

00:54:10.470 --> 00:54:12.680
but we'll be feeling a
lot more in the future.

00:54:12.680 --> 00:54:14.680
JAMIE JONES: Well, I have
pretty strong opinions

00:54:14.680 --> 00:54:17.070
about the way we
value the future,

00:54:17.070 --> 00:54:25.350
and I think that it seems like
it's a bit of a moral argument.

00:54:25.350 --> 00:54:29.940
But when we say we want to take
some steps to mitigate climate

00:54:29.940 --> 00:54:33.061
change now, whenever we do a
cost benefit analysis, what's

00:54:33.061 --> 00:54:34.560
going to happen is
that you're going

00:54:34.560 --> 00:54:41.790
to take a discount rate of the
value of an investment today

00:54:41.790 --> 00:54:43.500
a couple hundred
years in the future.

00:54:43.500 --> 00:54:44.780
And that's the real rub.

00:54:44.780 --> 00:54:49.320
It's both the fact
that you're valuing

00:54:49.320 --> 00:54:51.840
the present more than the
future, but you're also--

00:54:51.840 --> 00:54:55.330
all these things play out
at very long time scales.

00:54:55.330 --> 00:54:57.960
So you throw in a
4% discount rate,

00:54:57.960 --> 00:55:01.410
and it's very difficult to
come up with a cost benefit

00:55:01.410 --> 00:55:04.620
analysis that favors mitigation
now with a 4% discount

00:55:04.620 --> 00:55:08.560
rate that pays out its
benefits in 200 years.

00:55:08.560 --> 00:55:10.690
So I think, and I'm
not alone in this--

00:55:10.690 --> 00:55:13.890
there are a bunch of
environmental economists who

00:55:13.890 --> 00:55:16.590
are engaged in a very
vigorous debate on this--

00:55:16.590 --> 00:55:19.470
that we should use much
lower discount rates

00:55:19.470 --> 00:55:21.600
for thinking about
cost benefit analysis

00:55:21.600 --> 00:55:24.360
with these long payoffs.

00:55:24.360 --> 00:55:26.400
Martin Weitzman at
Harvard has suggested

00:55:26.400 --> 00:55:29.250
using the absolute
lowest discount

00:55:29.250 --> 00:55:34.980
rate that you can imagine
that makes it tenable, because

00:55:34.980 --> 00:55:40.410
of this problem, and because
the tail risk of these outcomes

00:55:40.410 --> 00:55:41.145
are so huge.

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:51.740
So that's something I take away
from this, like don't overvalue

00:55:51.740 --> 00:55:53.160
the present.

00:55:53.160 --> 00:55:54.530
But it's easy for me to do that.

00:55:54.530 --> 00:55:55.760
I live in Palo Alto, right?

00:55:55.760 --> 00:55:59.460
We all live in pretty
predictable environments.

00:55:59.460 --> 00:56:01.750
We're quite privileged
people, and it's easy to say,

00:56:01.750 --> 00:56:04.275
well, you know, we should
really value the future.

00:56:04.275 --> 00:56:06.900
And this is some of the
work that my colleagues

00:56:06.900 --> 00:56:09.150
who I showed you
briefly have done,

00:56:09.150 --> 00:56:11.660
showing that if you're poor--

00:56:11.660 --> 00:56:14.730
So like they're the classic
marshmallow experiments that

00:56:14.730 --> 00:56:16.890
were done here at Stanford.

00:56:16.890 --> 00:56:19.350
Give a kid a marshmallow
and walk away.

00:56:19.350 --> 00:56:20.750
Say, "Don't eat that, all right?

00:56:20.750 --> 00:56:23.560
Because if you do, that's
all you're getting.

00:56:23.560 --> 00:56:26.940
But if it's still there when
I come back, you get two."

00:56:26.940 --> 00:56:30.300
You walk away and it turns out
that these kids who struggle,

00:56:30.300 --> 00:56:31.725
they're looking at this
marshmallow, and they're going,

00:56:31.725 --> 00:56:32.225
"Oh god.

00:56:32.225 --> 00:56:34.110
I want to eat the
marshmallow so bad."

00:56:34.110 --> 00:56:36.300
It turns out that it
correlates very well--

00:56:36.300 --> 00:56:38.250
your ability to
put off that reward

00:56:38.250 --> 00:56:40.740
and get the larger reward
after a little delay--

00:56:40.740 --> 00:56:44.040
predicts a lot of things
about your success in life.

00:56:46.840 --> 00:56:50.040
It's really hard--
anthropologists have found it

00:56:50.040 --> 00:56:54.090
really hard to go into places
and replicate these types

00:56:54.090 --> 00:56:55.930
of economic games that
we play all the time,

00:56:55.930 --> 00:56:58.440
including the dictator games--

00:56:58.440 --> 00:57:01.920
these things that we
talked about before--

00:57:01.920 --> 00:57:03.690
in part because
people are like, how

00:57:03.690 --> 00:57:07.140
do I know you're going to be
back with your two marshmallows

00:57:07.140 --> 00:57:08.430
that you talk about?

00:57:08.430 --> 00:57:11.250
I've got to take that one
right now, thank you very much.

00:57:11.250 --> 00:57:14.550
And so that's just a cautionary
tale, that it's easy for me

00:57:14.550 --> 00:57:16.740
to say, we should
value the future more,

00:57:16.740 --> 00:57:21.180
because I have a pretty
low discount rate because I

00:57:21.180 --> 00:57:23.820
live in Palo Alto.

00:57:23.820 --> 00:57:30.770
As a society, I think we
should be modeling the future--

00:57:30.770 --> 00:57:34.020
valuing the future
more than we do.

00:57:34.020 --> 00:57:36.760
That's a really long answer
to a pretty straightforward

00:57:36.760 --> 00:57:39.070
question.

00:57:39.070 --> 00:57:40.610
Yeah, OK.

00:57:40.610 --> 00:57:44.680
AUDIENCE: How does
our evolution history

00:57:44.680 --> 00:57:48.070
play out when we are not
200 people in a small band?

00:57:48.070 --> 00:57:53.470
But we have 7 billion people
[INAUDIBLE] that we construct?

00:57:53.470 --> 00:57:55.690
JAMIE JONES: Yeah.

00:57:55.690 --> 00:58:01.690
That's a vexing problem, that
we sort of develop these ingroup

00:58:01.690 --> 00:58:03.910
and outgroup identities,
and that they probably

00:58:03.910 --> 00:58:06.610
are very functional when you
live in a band-like society,

00:58:06.610 --> 00:58:10.690
because your ingroup is
really your everything.

00:58:10.690 --> 00:58:13.690
It's maybe not so
functional when

00:58:13.690 --> 00:58:18.340
you make the rest of
the world your outgroup,

00:58:18.340 --> 00:58:21.640
and the same sort
of rules of morality

00:58:21.640 --> 00:58:25.790
don't apply to them
and that sort of thing.

00:58:25.790 --> 00:58:28.280
That's a real problem,
and solving that--

00:58:28.280 --> 00:58:32.990
there's a prize for someone,
is if we can figure out

00:58:32.990 --> 00:58:36.200
how to really begin
to address that.

00:58:36.200 --> 00:58:38.120
Equally importantly,
in the world

00:58:38.120 --> 00:58:43.180
we live in, when
you're a peasant farmer

00:58:43.180 --> 00:58:47.750
and you plant yams
and some maize

00:58:47.750 --> 00:58:53.150
and whatever, you place your
bet and then you tend it

00:58:53.150 --> 00:58:56.090
and you hopefully get
a big payoff, right?

00:58:56.090 --> 00:59:01.010
There is a direct causal
interpretation of what you do

00:59:01.010 --> 00:59:02.600
and what you get.

00:59:02.600 --> 00:59:05.810
In the world we live in, we
have all this complexity,

00:59:05.810 --> 00:59:08.930
and we don't necessarily pay
the costs for bad decisions

00:59:08.930 --> 00:59:11.300
right away, and I think that
makes it very hard to learn

00:59:11.300 --> 00:59:14.420
about good decision-making.

00:59:14.420 --> 00:59:16.730
And so there are
a number of people

00:59:16.730 --> 00:59:19.760
who've developed sort of the
curricula for teaching kids

00:59:19.760 --> 00:59:21.590
how to make risky decisions.

00:59:21.590 --> 00:59:26.217
I think that giving
kids some responsibility

00:59:26.217 --> 00:59:27.800
and getting them
some skin in the game

00:59:27.800 --> 00:59:29.010
is a really important thing.

00:59:29.010 --> 00:59:31.070
So that's a little
off of your question,

00:59:31.070 --> 00:59:33.800
but I think that that's another
real challenge to thinking

00:59:33.800 --> 00:59:36.202
about how our brains were
designed to make decisions

00:59:36.202 --> 00:59:37.910
and the types of
environments in which we

00:59:37.910 --> 00:59:41.090
have to do it now-- many of us.

00:59:41.090 --> 00:59:42.830
Yeah.

00:59:42.830 --> 00:59:45.530
AUDIENCE: If we predict
greatly increased variability

00:59:45.530 --> 00:59:48.145
in the near future,
what would you predict

00:59:48.145 --> 00:59:51.729
with those functions, e.g.

00:59:51.729 --> 00:59:54.730
more longevity or things
like that in this?

00:59:57.234 --> 00:59:58.650
JAMIE JONES: Well
first of all, we

00:59:58.650 --> 01:00:04.460
have to get through this
possible bottleneck, right?

01:00:04.460 --> 01:00:08.050
And I say that flippantly
because otherwise I'd just

01:00:08.050 --> 01:00:12.010
descend into depression, right?

01:00:12.010 --> 01:00:14.680
Sure, it's
conceivable that there

01:00:14.680 --> 01:00:20.279
could be more selection on even
more spread-out reproduction.

01:00:20.279 --> 01:00:21.070
The thing is that--

01:00:24.534 --> 01:00:26.200
a really interesting
observation that we

01:00:26.200 --> 01:00:28.840
make in development
economics and demography

01:00:28.840 --> 01:00:32.090
is that as soon
as you can ensure

01:00:32.090 --> 01:00:34.540
the more-or-less certain
survival of your kids

01:00:34.540 --> 01:00:37.000
to reproductive age,
people voluntarily

01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:40.580
reduce their fertility.

01:00:40.580 --> 01:00:45.460
And so we had this model called
the Demographic Transition

01:00:45.460 --> 01:00:48.910
model and it predicted the time
scale over which has happened,

01:00:48.910 --> 01:00:51.800
and it seemed to explain the
historical data very well.

01:00:51.800 --> 01:00:55.090
And then late in the 20th
century, these places--

01:00:55.090 --> 01:00:58.070
a lot of places in the
Middle East and North Africa

01:00:58.070 --> 01:00:59.770
and in Asia--

01:00:59.770 --> 01:01:01.990
in the tiger
economies, fertility

01:01:01.990 --> 01:01:06.775
fell like that as soon as kids
could be counted on to survive.

01:01:09.790 --> 01:01:13.812
And so-- yeah.

01:01:13.812 --> 01:01:18.040
If our technological
and social technologies

01:01:18.040 --> 01:01:21.910
can keep up with ensuring
the child survivorship

01:01:21.910 --> 01:01:28.090
and keeping it favoring
economic investment,

01:01:28.090 --> 01:01:30.220
then that sort of relaxes
the selection pressure

01:01:30.220 --> 01:01:32.960
to spread everything
out, for sure.

01:01:32.960 --> 01:01:37.000
And I think that that should
be a goal that we have.

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:39.910
If we want to avoid negative
population consequences,

01:01:39.910 --> 01:01:43.930
make sure that kids
survive to adulthood,

01:01:43.930 --> 01:01:47.800
because that changes everything
about people's investments,

01:01:47.800 --> 01:01:50.470
and that's really what this--

01:01:50.470 --> 01:01:54.580
given that you can't
affect that as a hominin

01:01:54.580 --> 01:01:58.390
a million years ago, you
don't have the technology

01:01:58.390 --> 01:02:00.430
to really mitigate that.

01:02:00.430 --> 01:02:03.680
So what you do is you
spread everything out.

01:02:03.680 --> 01:02:06.850
But if we have the chance
to actually solve it, then

01:02:06.850 --> 01:02:08.530
that's the better
solution probably,

01:02:08.530 --> 01:02:14.389
and that also reduces the
selective pressure, I think.

01:02:14.389 --> 01:02:14.888
Yeah.

01:02:14.888 --> 01:02:16.240
Yeah, thanks.

01:02:16.240 --> 01:02:16.899
[APPLAUSE]

01:02:16.899 --> 01:02:17.440
Thanks a lot.

01:02:17.440 --> 01:02:18.340
Thanks a lot.

01:02:18.340 --> 01:02:20.190
It was fun.

